---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
import ContentLayout from "../layouts/ContentLayout.astro";
import { sitePath } from "../utils/sitePath";

const loosePrompt = "Review this bugfix carefully. Stay read-only. Watch for behavior changes and missing tests. Do not edit code unless I approve a fix.";

const contractPrompt = "Operate under behavior-review. Review the current diff and report findings.";

const groundingSkillPrompt = "Use $personakit-grounding to resolve the requested PersonaKit session before acting.";
const groundingSkillHref = sitePath("tutorials/personakit-grounding/index.html");

const handoffCommands = `personakit validate --root .personakit
personakit contract --root .personakit --session behavior-review
personakit export --root .personakit --session behavior-review`;
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Learn PersonaKit"
  eyebrow="Mental map"
  description="How PersonaKit compares to prompts, skills, memory, the Managed Agents API, and MCP, and where it fits: availability is not authorization."
>
  <p>PersonaKit makes the most sense when you stop asking whether it replaces prompts, skills, memory, or compression. It does not. PersonaKit composes schema-backed project context into a resolved contract for the role, rules, stop points, allowed capabilities, and forbidden actions of a specific handoff.</p>

  <p>That matters more as agents get better. A capable agent with good memory and useful skills can still do the wrong extra thing unless the active work mode is visible before the work begins.</p>

  <h2 id="map">How It Compares To What You Already Use</h2>
  <p>You already use prompts, skills, memory, and maybe the Managed Agents API. PersonaKit does not replace them. It fills the gap each one leaves open, and the through-line is the same in every row: <strong>availability is not authorization</strong>.</p>
  <div class="compare-scroll">
    <table class="compare">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>What you already have</th>
          <th>What it does well</th>
          <th>What it can't do</th>
          <th>Where PersonaKit fits</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>System prompt, <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, <code>AGENTS.md</code></td>
          <td>Sets project-wide defaults the agent always sees.</td>
          <td>Cannot tell work modes apart in the same repo. Everything runs under one set of rules.</td>
          <td>PersonaKit layers sessions on top: same repo, a different contract per work mode.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Saved prompts, slash commands</td>
          <td>Reusable task starters that are easy to invoke.</td>
          <td>Rules live in plain text, so they cannot be validated, composed from pieces, or proven before handoff.</td>
          <td>PersonaKit makes the rules schema-backed, composable, and verifiable, not just text you paste.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Model memory</td>
          <td>Remembers preferences across conversations.</td>
          <td>Not authoritative, not inspectable by a teammate, not version-controlled, not proven before work starts.</td>
          <td>PersonaKit is a committed artifact, not a recalled preference. Anyone can read it and git tracks it.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Skills, host or API</td>
          <td>Teach the agent how to do something: a procedure.</td>
          <td>The skill exists whether or not it should run in this work mode.</td>
          <td>PersonaKit declares which skills are authorized for this session, not just which ones exist.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Managed Agents API</td>
          <td>Versioned, reusable agent configs with model, tools, and system prompt.</td>
          <td>The boundary is fixed when the agent is created. There is no per-session layer for "this one is read-only, that one implements."</td>
          <td>PersonaKit is per-session and per-work-mode. The same agent setup can run under different contracts.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>MCP servers</td>
          <td>Connect external context and capabilities to the agent.</td>
          <td>Connecting a server still only makes it available. It does not say whether it should be used this session.</td>
          <td>PersonaKit MCP exposes the resolved contract as read-only grounding, so the agent checks what is authorized before acting.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <Callout>
    <p><strong>Can't I just use the Managed Agents API for this?</strong> The Managed Agents API is the right layer for defining what an agent <em>is</em>: model, system prompt, tools, and skills, all versioned and reusable. PersonaKit is the layer for what an agent <em>does in a specific session</em>. The same agent setup can run under a read-only review contract one day and a bounded implementation contract the next. They compose well: PersonaKit does not replace the Agents API, it answers the question the Agents API leaves open, which is what is authorized for this session specifically.</p>
  </Callout>

  <section class="learning-path" aria-labelledby="releasedesk-path-heading">
    <p class="path-label">Recommended path</p>
    <h2 id="releasedesk-path-heading">Learn With ReleaseDesk</h2>
    <p>ReleaseDesk is the sample product: a tiny release-readiness dashboard with a real bug, a local readiness skill, and a completed PersonaKit root. Start by building its foundation, then continue with the same project through a normal engineering workday.</p>
    <ol class="path-steps">
      <li>
        <h3>Build The ReleaseDesk Foundation</h3>
        <p>Fix the readiness bug, then add PersonaKit only when agent boundaries become useful.</p>
        <a class="button-link path-action" href={sitePath("week-with-personakit/")}>Start the product lab</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3>Continue Into The Workday</h3>
        <p>Use that same ReleaseDesk project for review, approved follow-up, docs, and a host handoff. Return here after the foundation lab, or use the next-step card at the end of that tutorial.</p>
        <span class="path-next">Next after foundation</span>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <div class="learning-map" aria-label="Learning sections">
    <a href="#host-skill-front-door">Use a host skill</a>
    <a href="#contract">Read the contract</a>
    <a href="#compose">Compose the pieces</a>
    <a href="#prompt-to-contract">Turn a prompt into a contract</a>
    <a href="#handoff">Export handoff context</a>
  </div>

  <h2 id="host-skill-front-door">Use A Host Skill As The Front Door</h2>
  <p>If your agent host supports skills, a small grounding skill can make PersonaKit easier to invoke through autocomplete, fuzzy search, or a command palette. The host skill is only the front door: it resolves the PersonaKit contract before action, and PersonaKit remains the authority for what is allowed.</p>

  <Code code={groundingSkillPrompt} lang="text" theme="github-dark" />

  <p><a class="button-link" href={groundingSkillHref}>Open the PersonaKit grounding skill example</a></p>

  <h2 id="contract">Read The Contract</h2>
  <p>A resolved contract answers the questions that usually get scattered through chat history.</p>

  <div class="grid two">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Who Is Working?</h3>
      <p>The persona defines responsibilities, values, and non-goals.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>What Kind Of Work?</h3>
      <p>The directive defines steps, acceptance criteria, verification, and stop points.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Which Rules Apply?</h3>
      <p>Kits and essentials carry durable project guidance into the resolved payload.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Which Capabilities Are Allowed?</h3>
      <p>Skill authorization makes allowed and forbidden capabilities visible before work begins.</p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <h2 id="compose">Compose The Pieces</h2>
  <p>You define a session as the entry point. PersonaKit composes reusable parts into the resolved contract. Operators should not have to copy the same careful-review paragraph into every prompt or maintain several nearly identical skills just to change a boundary.</p>

  <Callout>
    <p><strong>Repo instructions and PersonaKit fit together:</strong> broad files such as AGENTS.md describe the default project rules. PersonaKit sessions select the situational work mode for a specific handoff.</p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="grid three compose-grid">
    <article class="card" id="persona">
      <h3>Persona</h3>
      <p>Who is acting.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card" id="directive">
      <h3>Directive</h3>
      <p>What kind of work this is.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Kit</h3>
      <p>Rules that should travel across related sessions.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Intent</h3>
      <p>Reusable work patterns and decision rails included by kits or required by directives.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Essentials</h3>
      <p>Required grounding that belongs in the resolved payload.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card" id="skills">
      <h3>Skills</h3>
      <p>Capabilities that may be authorized or forbidden for this lane.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Session</h3>
      <p>The composed lane that selects the pieces to resolve together.</p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <h3 class="composition-heading">Review Composition Example</h3>
  <p class="composition-intro">Review work shows why the pieces stay separate:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Composition</th>
        <th>Result</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>behavior-reviewer</code> + <code>behavior-preserving-review</code></td>
        <td>The existing read-only review lane reports findings without becoming the implementer.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Same reviewer + a different directive and session</td>
        <td>A conceptual implementation-after-approval lane could be separate instead of mutating the read-only lane.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shared review kit or essential</td>
        <td>Review discipline can travel across lanes without being pasted into each task prompt.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Same skill catalog, different sessions</td>
        <td>A capability can stay reusable while authorization is decided by the resolved contract.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="prompt-to-contract">Turn A Prompt Into A Contract</h2>
  <p>Start with a loose prompt:</p>

  <Code code={loosePrompt} lang="text" theme="github-dark" />

  <p>PersonaKit asks which parts are durable enough to become reusable structure:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Prompt Fragment</th>
        <th>Contract Piece</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Review this bugfix carefully.</td>
        <td>Persona: behavior reviewer.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Stay read-only.</td>
        <td>Skill boundary: authorize review, forbid editing.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Watch for behavior changes and missing tests.</td>
        <td>Directive: review steps and acceptance criteria.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Do not edit code unless I approve a fix.</td>
        <td>Stop point: implementation requires operator approval.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>The next prompt can shrink because the contract carries the repeated setup:</p>

  <Code code={contractPrompt} lang="text" theme="github-dark" />

  <p><a class="button-link" href={sitePath("examples/review-session/")}>Study the review-session example</a></p>

  <h2 id="handoff">Export Handoff Context</h2>
  <p>The practical loop is small and inspectable:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>Validate the authored PersonaKit root.</li>
    <li>Resolve the session contract.</li>
    <li>Inspect or export the context.</li>
    <li>Copy the exported grounding into the coding tool you use for the actual work.</li>
  </ol>

  <Code code={handoffCommands} lang="bash" theme="github-dark" />

  <Callout tone="good">
    <p>That is the craft: make the boundary durable, inspect it, and hand off only the context the contract resolved.</p>
  </Callout>

  <p class="action-row">
    <a class="button-link primary-path" href={sitePath("week-with-personakit/")}>Start the ReleaseDesk tutorial</a>
  </p>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .compare-scroll {
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .compare {
    min-width: 760px;
  }

  .learning-path {
    margin: 26px 0 34px;
    padding: 24px;
    border: 1px solid #dbe9ef;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #f7fbfd;
  }

  .learning-path h2 {
    margin: 2px 0 8px;
  }

  .learning-path > p:last-of-type {
    max-width: 760px;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .path-label {
    margin: 0;
    color: #46636f;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 750;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .path-steps {
    counter-reset: release-path;
    display: grid;
    gap: 12px;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    margin: 20px 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .path-steps li {
    counter-increment: release-path;
    padding: 16px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #fff;
  }

  .path-steps h3 {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .path-steps h3::before {
    content: counter(release-path);
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    flex: 0 0 auto;
    width: 24px;
    height: 24px;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: #eef6fa;
    color: var(--blue);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    font-weight: 800;
  }

  .path-steps p {
    margin: 0 0 14px;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .path-action {
    font-weight: 750;
  }

  .path-next {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 36px;
    padding: 7px 10px;
    border: 1px solid #d6e2e8;
    border-radius: 8px;
    color: #46636f;
    background: #f7fbfd;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    font-weight: 750;
  }

  .learning-map {
    display: grid;
    gap: 10px;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    margin: 24px 0 36px;
  }

  .learning-map a {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 54px;
    padding: 10px 12px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    color: var(--ink);
    background: #fff;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .learning-map a:hover {
    border-color: #9fb7c6;
    color: var(--blue);
  }

  .compose-grid {
    margin: 18px 0 30px;
  }

  .composition-heading {
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .composition-intro {
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }

  .action-row {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 10px;
  }

  .primary-path {
    border-color: #8db3c9;
    background: #eef6fa;
    color: var(--blue);
    font-weight: 750;
  }

  @media (max-width: 840px) {
    .path-steps {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .learning-map {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 520px) {
    .learning-map {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
